    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p><addressee>Rev. Mr I. Leeser</addressee>, <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <placeName>New York</placeName>
                <date>Sept 23th 1849</date>
            </p>
            <p>Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">It is a long time since I wanted to write to<lb/> you, but
                circumstances of different nature prevented<lb/> me from doing so. Being in this
                City for the<lb/> purpose of buying goods for fall trade, I take to<lb/> day an hour
                to communicate with you.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I am sorry, that I never could have the<lb/> pleasure of having a
                personal acquaintance with you<lb/> but as the old saying is, by your works you
                shall<lb/> be known, namely being a reader of your Occident<lb/> for the last 4
                years, I know you pretty near as well.<lb/> For my part I confess to you I take
                pride in being<lb/> a descendant of our <sic>comon</sic> grandfather
                    <persName>Jacob</persName>, I feel<lb/> gratification in reading your
                Periodical, &amp; the stand you<lb/> have taken in the <sic>defence</sic> of our
                holy Religion against<lb/> trespassers from amongst ourselves, &amp; its
                columinators<lb/> from without. I admire your perseverance &amp; <del>eng</del>
                energy<lb/> in pursuing your work for the welfare of <placeName>Israel</placeName>,
                &amp; most<lb/> of all, the adherency to one &amp; the same tendency of your<lb/>
                writings, the looking ahead to the one glorious end of<lb/> enlightening our
                brethren in the sublime system of the<lb/> Mosaic law &amp; precepts, as handed down
                to us by our forefathers<lb/> it being our duty, to transmit the same to the
                next<lb/> generation unimpaired, not <sic>modelled</sic>, but remaining<lb/> the
                same, as the God who gave it, to the last end of time,</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Being a German myself, I am sorry to<lb/> confess, that there is
                amongst that portion of <add>יהודים</add> from<lb/> our Fatherland who are of the
                middle age very little<lb/> Intelligence or any wish at all to read a religious
                paper<lb/> or your work might have done more good already.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">The younger portion, those from 18<add>?</add>—to 30<lb/> mostly
                think themselves Philosophers, every one thinks<lb/> himself a great man, what do we
                care about Religion<lb/> be a Gentleman, make money, &amp; mockery at those<lb/> who
                hold fast to the <sic>tenents</sic> of our holy Law, most<lb/> of them ashamed to
                own themselves Jews, &amp; here you<lb/> have got a Picture of the fathers of our
                next generation<lb/> to come. Our rich men, our men of Capital what<lb/> are they
                doing for the cause of Religion? They give<lb/> a 100 or so for to build a new
                Synagogue, another<lb/> 100 towards benevolent purposes, &amp; here is an end of
                it.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">What will Judaism be in 50 years<lb/> in the great Republic, if the
                mind of those young<lb/> would be Philosophers, if the <sic>indifferentisness</sic>
                of our<lb/> rich men towards our holy law, if the unintelligence<lb/> of the masses
                of the Jews is not aroused, &amp; the<lb/> question agitated, have we no other duty
                to perform<lb/> towards our almighty Father, but to pray on <add>ר"ה י"כ ראש השנה
                    יום כיפור</add><lb/> in the Synagogue, pay a few Dollars for maintaining<lb/>
                the Congregation &amp; charitable Society, &amp; then leave<lb/> the whole system to
                itself;—</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Is the reform of our service in the Synagogue<lb/> all we can do, to
                transmit our holy Law to generations<lb/> to come? Is it not necessary first to
                impress each &amp; every<lb/> one that the great gift of our heavenly Father the
                    <add>שבת</add><lb/> should be strictly kept? Shall we not have a Union<lb/> of
                all the Congregations of the <placeName>U. S.</placeName> to contribute all<lb/> for
                the erection of a Jewish University &amp; seats of<lb/> learning, to educate
                ministers teachers &amp; readers?<lb/> Should we not have a Jewish Hospital in the
                City<lb/> of <placeName>N York</placeName>, paid &amp; kept by the Contributions of
                all the<lb/> Jews of the <placeName>U. States</placeName>? Could we not have
                    <date>Sabbath</date><lb/>
                <sic>shool</sic> Societies in each &amp; ever congregation in the Land<lb/> as well
                as the Methodists? —</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Those were some of my ideas, my friend, when<lb/> I took the pen to
                write to you, &amp; I hope that you will<lb/> excuse a layman for meddling in
                religious concerns, which<lb/> belong more to the minister in the pulpit, but I
                could<lb/> not forbear to write them down, &amp; let you peruse them.<lb/> Now to
                business of mine. Those <add>תפילות</add> you once<lb/> wrote to me of having send
                the <sic>trough</sic> a house in this<lb/> city &amp; another in
                    <placeName>Chicago</placeName>, I never received, please<lb/> to inquire about
                them, or give me orders, where to make<lb/> inquiry here. I shall stay here about a
                fortnight longer<lb/> &amp; be pleased to tell me, how much <persName>I Kohn &amp;
                    Bros</persName><lb/> are in your debt for Occident, I have once remitted<lb/> to
                you = Ten Dollars. I shall afford me<lb/> pleasure to receive a line or two from
                you, meanwhile<lb/> I have the honor to remain respectfully <persName role="author"
                    >A Kohn</persName><lb/> from <placeName>Chicago</placeName> care of
                    <persName>Schloss Heilbronn</persName>
                <placeName>47 Norfolk<lb/> str N. York</placeName></p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
            <p>paid</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <addressee>Rev. I Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Editor of the Occident,</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <placeName>Pa</placeName>
            </p>
        </body>
